{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538897"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:34:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:34:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16418"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16418"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0.11,0.11,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107964"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9109"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90377"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1372"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21637"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40272"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107964"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following an assault. He was stabbed in the left chest wall. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears pale and diaphoretic. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. There is a 2 cm laceration in the left fifth intercostal space, mid-axillary line. His chest is dull to percussion on the left side with reduced breath sounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray shows a large left-sided pleural effusion. Two large-bore intravenous lines are inserted and blood is sent for full blood count, coagulation profile, group and crossmatch. Normal saline is commenced and O negative blood is requested. A large-bore chest drain is inserted, draining 1500 mL of blood immediately.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Insert a second chest drain","Urgent computed tomography of chest","Commence intravenous tranexamic acid","Transfer to intensive care unit","Urgent thoracic surgical review"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a massive haemothorax following penetrating chest trauma. The immediate drainage of 1500 mL of blood indicates significant intrathoracic bleeding. Given the patient\u0027s unstable vital signs and the large volume of blood loss, it is very likely that urgent surgical intervention will be required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent thoracic surgical review\u003C/strong\u003E is essential as the patient may require emergency thoracotomy. Indications for thoracotomy in haemothorax include initial drainage of \u003E1500 mL blood, ongoing blood loss \u003E200 mL/hr for two to four hours, or haemodynamic instability despite resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsert a second chest drain\u003C/strong\u003E is not going to resolve the problem and will only delay what is very likely to be an urgent trip to the operating theatre. Any delay in the definitive management could lead to further deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent computed tomography of chest\u003C/strong\u003E would delay definitive management and may be dangerous in an unstable patient. While imaging is important, the clinical picture already indicates the need for surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence intravenous tranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful as an adjunct therapy but should not delay surgical consultation. It is not the primary management strategy for massive haemothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to intensive care unit\u003C/strong\u003E may eventually be necessary but should not occur before surgical review and potential operative intervention. The immediate priority is to control the source of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Early thoracic surgical consultation is essential in massive haemothorax to assess need for thoracotomy.","Initial management of haemothorax includes large-bore chest drain insertion, fluid resuscitation, and urgent blood product administration.","Ongoing blood loss \u003E200 mL/hr through chest drain is an indication for surgical intervention."],"references":["Dennis BM, Bellister SA, Guillamondegui OD. Thoracic Trauma. Surg Clin N Am 97 2017;  97:1047\u201364"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90377"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16418"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90377"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-05T12:09:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T12:11:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9109"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107964"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"R